<h1>Best Log Books for Beekeepers in 2026</h1>
<p><em>Updated June 2026 | 6-minute read</em></p>

<div class="tldr">
<strong>Short version:</strong> Hive inspection records are the difference between reacting to problems and preventing them. The best beekeeper log books track queen status, brood pattern, honey stores, varroa mite counts, and treatments in one place — organized by hive and date so you can actually compare across inspections.
</div>

<p>Experienced beekeepers keep records. New beekeepers think they'll remember. Three inspections in, with multiple hives, you won't.</p>

<p>What you need to track per inspection: date and weather conditions, queen status (seen/eggs/brood pattern), population estimate, honey and pollen stores, signs of disease or pests, varroa mite wash count if performed, any treatments applied, and notes on temperament. That's 9 data points per visit, per hive, across every inspection of the season.</p>

<p>A structured log book makes this fast. A blank notebook makes it inconsistent — you'll record different things each time and won't be able to compare across visits.</p>

<h2>What to Look For</h2>

<p>The best hive inspection log books have pre-structured forms (not blank pages), enough space per entry for real notes, a seasonal summary section for end-of-year review, and a hive ID system so records from multiple hives stay separated. Bonus points for varroa tracking pages and treatment logs built in.</p>

<h2>Our Top Picks</h2>

<div class="product-card">
<h3>1. Beekeeper's Hive Inspection Log — Multi-Hive Edition</h3>
<p class="rating">★★★★★ — Best Overall</p>
<p>Structured for beekeepers managing 1–10 hives. Each inspection entry covers all 9 essential data points with checkboxes and fill-in fields, so recording is fast even mid-inspection with gloves on. Organized by hive ID, then chronologically within each hive section.</p>

<p>The standout feature: a seasonal health summary page for each hive, where you can record overwintering weight, spring buildup rate, and first honey super date. After 2–3 seasons, patterns emerge that help you predict which hives will be strongest producers and which struggle in your local climate.</p>

<p>Varroa tracking: dedicated mite wash log with threshold markers (1 mite per 100 bees = treatment threshold for most regions). Treatment log records product, dose, dates applied, and date removed.</p>

<p><strong>Best for:</strong> Hobbyist beekeepers managing 2–8 hives who want a complete record system for the full season.</p>
<p><strong>Size:</strong> 8.5×11 | <strong>Pages:</strong> 160 | <strong>Price:</strong> ~$14.99</p>
</div>

<div class="product-card">
<h3>2. Beginning Beekeeper's First-Year Journal</h3>
<p class="rating">★★★★½ — Best for New Beekeepers</p>
<p>Designed for first-year beekeepers who don't yet know what they're looking for. Each inspection page has a visual guide to what healthy brood looks like (capped, uncapped, eggs, empty cells) with checkboxes matching the diagram. This turns the learning curve into a checklist rather than a memory test.</p>

<p>Includes a monthly calendar section for timing seasonal tasks: when to add supers, when to check for swarm cells, when to do varroa counts, when to apply oxalic acid treatment. The calendar is blank (not pre-filled with dates) so it works for any year and any region.</p>

<p><strong>Best for:</strong> New beekeepers in their first 1–2 seasons learning what to look for and when.</p>
<p><strong>Size:</strong> 6×9 | <strong>Pages:</strong> 140 | <strong>Price:</strong> ~$12.99</p>
</div>

<div class="product-card">
<h3>3. Varroa Management & Treatment Log</h3>
<p class="rating">★★★★ — Best Specialized Varroa Tracker</p>
<p>Dedicated to the single biggest threat to managed honeybee colonies: varroa mite infestation. Tracks alcohol wash counts, sugar roll counts, drone brood uncapping results, and all treatments (oxalic acid vaporization, Apivar strips, Apiguard, etc.) with dates, dosages, and re-test dates.</p>

<p>Many beekeepers lose colonies to varroa because they don't track mite counts consistently enough to catch infestations before they exceed treatment thresholds. This log makes consistent tracking the default rather than something you do when you remember to.</p>

<p><strong>Best for:</strong> Any beekeeper who has lost a colony to varroa or wants to take IPM (integrated pest management) seriously.</p>
<p><strong>Size:</strong> 6×9 | <strong>Pages:</strong> 120 | <strong>Price:</strong> ~$11.99</p>
</div>

<h2>Digital vs. Paper for Hive Records</h2>

<p>Apps like Hive Tracks and ApiaryBook exist. They're fine, especially if you're managing 20+ hives commercially. For hobbyist beekeepers with 1–10 hives, paper wins for speed: you're in the hive, wearing gloves, holding a frame. Tapping a phone screen with sticky gloves is slower than filling a checkbox with a pencil.</p>

<p>The hybrid approach works well: paper log in the field during the inspection, photo of the log pages at the end, photo stored in a phone folder organized by hive. You get the speed of paper and the backup of digital.</p>

<h2>The Record You'll Actually Be Glad You Kept</h2>

<p>Three years into beekeeping, the record you'll be most grateful for isn't the honey harvest log. It's the queen history: when each queen was introduced, whether she was marked, her egg-laying pattern over her life, and when you replaced her.</p>

<p>Queen quality degrades over time. A 3-year-old queen is statistically more likely to fail than a 1-year-old. Beekeepers who track queen age and pattern can replace queens proactively, before the colony declines. Those who don't often lose the hive trying to figure out why production dropped.</p>

<p>The log book is the queen record. Everything else is a bonus.</p>

